<CHARACTERISTICS_OF_STUDIES>
<CHARACTERISTICS_OF_INCLUDED_STUDIES SORT_BY="STUDY" USER_DEF_1_ENABLED="NO" USER_DEF_2_ENABLED="NO" USER_DEF_3_ENABLED="NO">
<INCLUDED_CHAR STUDY_ID="STD-Ring-1998">
<CHAR_METHODS>
<P>Two groups of patients were randomly allocated to different post-operative therapy regimes, following MCP arthroplasty with Swanson prostheses.<BR/>Randomisation: unmet; investigators assigned alternate hands to each treatment group; however the authors used individual fingers as the unit of analysis (without adjustment for the non-independent cluster design)<BR/>Allocation concealment: inadequate<BR/>Blinding: unmet; participants and outcome assessors were not blinded (outcome assessor described as independent)<BR/>Completeness of follow up: unmet; 5 people (3 in the intervention, 2 in the control group) missed a follow-up assessment for unknown reasons and were excluded from the study and analysis. 2 people were moved from the intervention to the control group for clinical reasons and were analysed on an as-treated basis. There was incomplete preoperative assessment of some subjects.<BR/>Explicit diagnostic criteria: met; same for both groups<BR/>Explicit outcome criteria: met; same for both groups<BR/>Baseline differences in experimental groups: unclear; not assessed statistically but the two groups appear similar in age range, proportion with surgery in dominant and non-dominant hands, time since diagnosis, pre-operative range of motion, preoperative grip strength, and preoperative lateral pinch strength.<BR/>Overall assessment of quality: high risk of bias.</P>
</CHAR_METHODS>
<CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<P>22 adults with RA, 10 in the treatment group (seven men and three women) and 12 in control (six men and six women). They were aged 30-75 years.<BR/>The treatment group had a mean of 34 degrees of motion, and the controls had a mean of 25 degrees of motion, pre-operatively, at the MCP joint<BR/>Inclusion criteria: participants with rheumatoid arthritis and disabling hand deformities, who were recommended for metacarpophalangeal silicone rubber interposition arthroplasty of the index, long, ring and small fingers.<BR/>Exclusion criteria: participants with recurrent deformities following a previous silicone rubber interposition.</P>
</CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<P>Treatment: dynamic MCP extension splinting and continuous passive motion as tolerated for six weeks; and participants wore a static MCP extension splinting at night. <BR/>Control: dynamic extension splinting (control) and exercises in the splint for 6 weeks.<BR/>Dynamic splinting continued for 6 weeks post-operatively and functional use of the hand was discouraged for six weeks post-operatively in both groups.</P>
</CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<P>1) Range of motion, MCP joint<BR/>2) Ulnar deviation MCP joint<BR/>3) Grip strength<BR/>4) Lateral pinch strength<BR/>Outcomes were measured pre-operatively and at 6 months post-operatively.</P>
</CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<CHAR_NOTES>
<P>Bias may have occurred in the intervention - patients used CPM as tolerated and may have received different amounts of CPM. <BR/>It appears the unit of allocation to treatment was the hand, but the unit of analysis was the individual finger, without a correction for the cluster design (i.e. no measure of the intracluster correlation coefficient); which tends to result in artificially small P-values and overestimation of the effect of the intervention. <BR/>The authors state that they present the mean and 95% CIs for outcomes; however our interpretation of the methods of analysis indicate that 95% CI's were probably not calculated, and it is unclear what measure of variance is actually presented (possibly standard deviations, or standard errors of the mean). We have attempted to contact the authors to clarify the data.<BR/>Due to the unit of analysis and uncertainty of the variance presented, at present the data is not in a form that could be used in a meta-analysis.<BR/>The study was graded as low quality because of the potential for selection bias due to inadequate methods of randomisation and failure to conceal treatment allocation, and potential for bias in equality of treatment and incomplete measurement of outcome.</P>
</CHAR_NOTES>
</INCLUDED_CHAR>
<FOOTNOTES/>
