<CHARACTERISTICS_OF_EXCLUDED_STUDIES SORT_BY="STUDY">
<EXCLUDED_CHAR STUDY_ID="STD-Burr-_x0026_-Pratt-1999">
<CHAR_REASON_FOR_EXCLUSION>
<P>Case study, N=1. The patient received static splinting in MCP flexion one day and MCP extension the next, for four weeks.<BR/>0-15 MCP extension and 60-70 MCP flexion at 8/52. Bias possible in detection of all outcomes (pre-operative data not complete).</P>
</CHAR_REASON_FOR_EXCLUSION>
</EXCLUDED_CHAR>
<EXCLUDED_CHAR STUDY_ID="STD-Burr-_x0026_-Pratt-2001">
<CHAR_REASON_FOR_EXCLUSION>
<P>Case series design, N=15. Patients received static splinting in MCP flexion one day and MCP extension the next, for four weeks. Mean MCP flexion unchanged. Improvements in pain, MCP extension and power grip. Bias possible in patient selection.</P>
</CHAR_REASON_FOR_EXCLUSION>
</EXCLUDED_CHAR>
<EXCLUDED_CHAR STUDY_ID="STD-Gribben-1981">
<CHAR_REASON_FOR_EXCLUSION>
<P>Case study, N=1. The patient received a dynamic MCP extension splint during the day and a static MCP extension splint at night for 10 weeks. The patient had 10 degrees less MCP flexion than preoperatively, 5 months post, but reduced pain and paraesthsiae. Bias possible in patient selection.</P>
</CHAR_REASON_FOR_EXCLUSION>
</EXCLUDED_CHAR>
<EXCLUDED_CHAR STUDY_ID="STD-Groth-1996">
<CHAR_REASON_FOR_EXCLUSION>
<P>Retrospective case series. N=34 patients (46 hands). The patients received either a dynamive extension protocol (control) or a dynamic flexion protocol (treatment), with static splinting at night (MCP 20-30 degrees flexion). The treatment group had significantly more MSP flexion than cohort, but similar MSP extension. Bias possible in patient selection and detection of all outcomes.</P>
</CHAR_REASON_FOR_EXCLUSION>
</EXCLUDED_CHAR>
<EXCLUDED_CHAR STUDY_ID="STD-Thomsen-2003">
<CHAR_REASON_FOR_EXCLUSION>
<P>Retrospective series of 24 patients (aged 43-74 years) , where 22 were followed up post-operatively. Thirteen had received dynamic MCP splinting (treatment) after MCP arthroplasty and they were seen 3-8 years post-operatively. Nine patients did not have dynamic splinting post-operatively (control), and they were seen 1.6-4 years post-operatively. The treatment group had significantly (P=0.002) more active MCP extension than the control group. Bias possible in patient selection and detection of all outcomes.</P>
</CHAR_REASON_FOR_EXCLUSION>
</EXCLUDED_CHAR>
